================================================================
BLUE DOLPHIN ENERGY COMPANY (OTCQX: BDCO)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, filed May 15, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Top-line declined steadily over the past three years. Revenue was $396.0m in FY23, declined to $317.5m in FY24 (down (19.8%) / ($78.5m) YoY) on weaker refining margins, lower sales volumes, and an $8.3m inventory impairment, and fell further to $279.4m in FY25 (down (12.0%) / ($38.1m) YoY) on continued margin pressure. Q1 FY26 revenue was $81.5m vs $83.7m in Q1 FY25, down (2.6%) / ($2.2m) YoY — broadly stable while gross margins expanded sharply on favorable product differentials and inventory impacts.

> Profitability: Profitability rebounded sharply in Q1 FY26 from depressed FY24-FY25 levels. For FY25, gross margin was 3.1% vs 1.2% in FY24 (+190 bps), consolidated EBITDA turned positive at $1.3m from ($1.5m), and net loss narrowed to ($5.6m) from ($8.6m).

In Q1 FY26, gross margin expanded to 25.3% from 7.3% in Q1 FY25 — up ~1,800 bps — driven by favorable product differentials, inventory impacts, and a $1.0m BSEE regulatory settlement gain. Net income surged to $14.7m vs $2.2m in Q1 FY25 (a $12.5m swing); consolidated EBITDA was $20.7m vs $5.1m, with Refining EBITDA of $18.6m vs $4.9m.

> Cash Flows: Q1 FY26 generated strong operating cash flow on the earnings rebound, but cash slipped to $1.4m at March 31, 2026 from $2.0m at year-end 2025 as inventory built to $37.7m from $30.9m, mainly on naphtha.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of March 31, 2026, cash and restricted cash totaled $1.4m (incl. $1.0m payment-reserve at Huntington). Third-party long-term debt was $35.0m, with all three core facilities — LE Term Loan Due 2034, LRM Term Loan Due 2034, and NPS Term Loan Due 2031 — in default on financial covenants; related-party debt is also in default.

> Working Capital: Working capital deficit widened to $24.4m at YE25 from $19.1m at YE24. Q1 FY26 inventory rose to $37.7m from $30.9m, mainly naphtha — supplier-credit dependency is acute given thin cash.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: Management is optimizing the 15,000-bpd Nixon refinery, improving flare-gas monitoring, and pursuing renewable-energy growth while continuing efforts to refinance and restructure the defaulted debt facilities.

> Going Concern: Management identified historical working capital deficits and significant debt in default as conditions requiring going-concern evaluation, though currently expects to meet obligations for at least one year. No explicit "substantial doubt" statement.

> Related-Party & Governance Overhang: An Affiliate and CEO Jonathan Carroll together control ~83% of voting power; the Affiliate also funds working capital, guarantees certain secured debt, and is a significant customer — concentrated control with deep operational entanglement.

> Management Change: CEO Jonathan P. Carroll is the long-tenured leader with significant insider ownership; he purchased $92,363 of stock in April 2025. No major management turnover — stable but tightly controlled by founder-CEO.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. FY25 10-K filed March 31, 2026 and Q1 FY26 10-Q filed May 15, 2026, both on schedule with no Form 12b-25 extension reported.

